{"parse":{"title":"Irena's Vow","pageid":22352779,"revid":812964410,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Irena's Vow</b></i> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Broadway_theatre\" title=\"Broadway theatre\">Broadway</a> play recounting the story of <a href=\"/wiki/Irena_Gut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Irena Gut\">Irena Gut</a>, a Polish nurse who, at the risk of her life, saved twelve <a href=\"/wiki/Jew\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Jew\">Jews</a> during <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Nazi_Germany\" title=\"Nazi Germany\">German</a>-<a href=\"/wiki/Occupied_Poland\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Occupied Poland\">occupied Poland</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-playbill_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-playbill-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Production_history\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Production history</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Story\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Story</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Production_history\">Production history</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Production history\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The play opened at Broadway's <a href=\"/wiki/Walter_Kerr_Theatre\" title=\"Walter Kerr Theatre\">Walter Kerr Theatre</a> at 219 West 48th Street (between Broadway and 8th Avenue) on 29 March 2009,<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> after having premiered off-Broadway at the Baruch Performing Arts Center in September 2008. The ninety-minute play opened at the Kerr Theatre with the same cast from off-Broadway.<sup id=\"cite_ref-playbill_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-playbill-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The play was written by <a href=\"/wiki/Dan_Gordon_(screenwriter)\" title=\"Dan Gordon (screenwriter)\">Dan Gordon</a>, based on conversations that he had held with Irene Gut-Opdyke (<i>n\u00e9e</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Irena_Gut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Irena Gut\">Irena Gut</a>). Gordon \"captures... peculiarly Polish elements: the heroine's irony and sense of humor in the face of catastrophe.\" He deftly draws the historic backdrop to Irena's story and creates a suspenseful narrative and \"enthralling dialog.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The title role is played by <a href=\"/wiki/Tovah_Feldshuh\" title=\"Tovah Feldshuh\">Tovah Feldshuh</a>. Appearing in other roles are Sandi Carroll, <a href=\"/wiki/Tracee_Chimo\" title=\"Tracee Chimo\">Tracee Chimo</a>, Steven Hauck, Scott Klaven, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Peter_Reznikoff&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Peter Reznikoff (page does not exist)\">Peter Reznikoff</a>, Thomas Ryan, Gene Silvers, John Stanisci and <a href=\"/wiki/Maja_Wampuszyc\" title=\"Maja Wampuszyc\">Maja Wampuszyc</a>.\n</p><p><i>Irena's Vow</i> is directed by Michael Parva. Scenic design is by Kevin Judge; lighting design, David Castaneda; costume design, Astrid Brucker; sound design and music composition, Quentin Chiappetta; and projection design, Alex Koch.<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-playbill_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-playbill-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On June 16, 2009 it was announced that <i>Irena's Vow</i> will close on June 28.  At the time of its closure, it will have played 21 previews and 105 regular performances.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Story\">Story</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Story\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>After <a href=\"/wiki/Poland\" title=\"Poland\">Poland</a> was invaded by <a href=\"/wiki/German_invasion_of_Poland\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"German invasion of Poland\">Germany</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_invasion_of_Poland\" title=\"Soviet invasion of Poland\">Soviet Union</a> in September 1939, <a href=\"/wiki/Irena_Gut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Irena Gut\">Irena Gut</a>, a Polish <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Church\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roman Catholic Church\">Catholic</a> nurse nineteen year old at the outbreak of <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a>, was captured by the Soviet Army. After escaping, she was caught in a German <a href=\"/wiki/%C5%81apanka\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"\u0141apanka\">roundup</a> to be used as a <a href=\"/wiki/Slave_labor\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Slave labor\">slave laborer</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Eventually she became the housekeeper to a German army major. After she witnessed the gruesome fate of <a href=\"/wiki/Jew\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Jew\">Jews</a> in German-occupied Poland, Gut resolved at the risk of her life to conceal a dozen Jews threatened by the German <a href=\"/wiki/Holocaust\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Holocaust\">Holocaust</a> extermination program. The penalty that the Germans imposed on any Pole found to be harboring or otherwise aiding Jews was death.<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>One day Gut's employer discovered that she was concealing Jews in his house. Gut begged him to spare them; he agreed to, and never betrayed them or her. Gut became the German officer's mistress. Before the <a href=\"/wiki/Red_Army\" title=\"Red Army\">Red Army</a> arrived, she fled with the people that she was protecting into the forest. After the war, suspected falsely by some of having collaborated with the Germans, she emigrated to the United States.<sup id=\"cite_ref-polestar_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-polestar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Irena_Gut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Irena Gut\">Irena Gut</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/List_of_individuals_and_groups_assisting_Jews_during_the_Holocaust\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"List of individuals and groups assisting Jews during the Holocaust\">List of individuals and groups assisting Jews during the Holocaust</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Rescue_of_Jews_by_Poles_during_the_Holocaust\" title=\"Rescue of Jews by Poles during the Holocaust\">Rescue of Jews by Poles during the Holocaust</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=2009_in_theatre&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"2009 in theatre (page does not exist)\">2009 in theatre</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-playbill-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-playbill_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-playbill_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-playbill_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Andrew Gans, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.playbill.com/news/article/124530.html\">\"Feldshuh to Return to Broadway in March in Irena's Vow\"</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20081225003521/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/124530.html\">Archived</a> 2008-12-25 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>., playbill.com, 22 December 2008.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-polestar-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-polestar_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"<i>Przysi\u0119ga Ireny</i>\" (\"Irena's Vow\"), <i>Gwiazda Polarna</i> (Pole Star), vol. 100, no. 7 (March 28, 2009), p. 14.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Gans, Andrew.<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://archive.is/20120907082649/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/130282\">\"Irena's Vow to Close on Broadway June 28,\"</a> playbill.com, June 16, 2009</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>\"<i>Przysi\u0119ga Ireny</i>\" (\"Irena's Vow\"), <i><a href=\"/wiki/Gwiazda_Polarna\" title=\"Gwiazda Polarna\">Gwiazda Polarna</a></i> (Pole Star), vol. 100, no. 7 (March 28, 2009), p. 14.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Irena%27s_Vow&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=482325\">Internet Broadway Database listing</a></li>\n<li>Andrew Gans, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20081225003521/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/124530.html\">\"Feldshuh to Return to Broadway in March in Irena's Vow\"</a>, playbill.com, 22 De